First, we need to find the symmetric difference of A and B, denoted as A ∆ B. The symmetric difference is the set of elements which are in either of the sets A or B, but not in both. 

A ∆ B = (A - B) ∪ (B - A) = {1, 3} ∪ {4, 5} = {1, 3, 4, 5}

Now, we can find the Cartesian product of (A ∆ B) and C, denoted as (A ∆ B) x C. The Cartesian product is the set of all ordered pairs (a, c) where a is in A ∆ B and c is in C.

(A ∆ B) x C = {(1, 6), (1, 7), (3, 6), (3, 7), (4, 6), (4, 7), (5, 6), (5, 7)}

Next, we find the symmetric difference of B and A, denoted as B ∆ A. Since the symmetric difference is commutative, B ∆ A is equal to A ∆ B.

B ∆ A = A ∆ B = {1, 3, 4, 5}

Now, we can find the Cartesian product of (B ∆ A) and C, denoted as (B ∆ A) x C.

(B ∆ A) x C = {(1, 6), (1, 7), (3, 6), (3, 7), (4, 6), (4, 7), (5, 6), (5, 7)}

Comparing the two Cartesian products, we can see that (A ∆ B) x C is equal to (B ∆ A) x C:

(A ∆ B) x C = (B ∆ A) x C = {(1, 6), (1, 7), (3, 6), (3, 7), (4, 6), (4, 7), (5, 6), (5, 7)}

Therefore, the symmetric difference of A and B with respect to C is commutative in this case.
